1. requests.get(url): This instructs Python to establish a network connection to the target URL. It handles the entire under-the-hood low-level TCP/IP handshake and 
sends an HTTP GET request, just like a standard web browser

2. timeout=5: This is a defensive programming safeguard. If the target server is down or stuck in a slow network loop, this parameter forces the script to break the 
connection after 5 seconds instead of letting your scanner hang forever.

3. response.headers: When a server answers an HTTP request, it doesn't just send the webpage content; it sends a hidden administrative dictionary map containing 
instructions for the web browser.

4. if header in response.headers: Your script loops through this dictionary to look for critical security flags. For example, if X-Frame-Options is missing, it lets 
your engine instantly flag that the site lacks protections against Clickjacking attacks.

5. response.text: This fetches the completely raw, messy, raw HTML string source code directly out of the server's network response package.

6. BeautifulSoup(..., "html.parser"): Raw HTML is incredibly difficult to search through using plain text rules. This command takes that massive string and turns it into 
a structured object tree called a Document Object Model (DOM)

7. soup.find_all("form"): This method searches through the parsed HTML tree structure and pulls every single <form ...> </form> tag block it finds into a clean Python list.

8. form.get("action"): In web development, the action attribute dictates where the user's data gets transmitted when they hit submit (in your output, it showed /post).

9. form.get("method"): This dictates how the data is sent. If it uses GET, data is attached directly to the URL string (e.g., website.com/login?password=123). Your code 
checks for this to flag parameter exposure vulnerabilities! If it uses POST, data is packaged invisibly inside the request body payload.

10. .upper(): This is a data normalization trick. HTML allows developers to write methods as lowercase post or uppercase POST. .upper() forces everything to uppercase so 
our comparison logic (if method == "GET":) never fails due to a casing mismatch.

11. enumerate(forms, start=1): Instead of just looping through the forms, enumerate tracks a counter variable automatically. Setting start=1 means your terminal prints 
out clean human-readable labels like Form #1 instead of computer-indexed labels like Form #0.

12. form.find_all("input"): Instead of scanning the whole website, this limits the search to only the current form block, harvesting every data field text box, 
radio button, or checkbox.

13. input_field.get("name"): This is the parameter key that the server processes. For a penetration tester, knowing names like custname or custemail tells them exactly
what variable variables to target with malicious injection strings during an exploit test.

14. from urllib.parse import urljoin: Web forms often use short relative paths like <form action="/post">. The urljoin command intelligently splices the baseline 
address (https://httpbin.org) with that short action path to construct a complete, valid network endpoint path (https://httpbin.org/post).

15. submit_data[input_name] = xss_payload: This builds a dictionary string payload. It maps the form fields (like custname) directly to our malicious string injection 
test (<script>alert('Vulnerable!')</script>).

16. requests.post(target_url, data=submit_data): This fires a real server-side weapon simulation. It pushes all our malicious testing text directly over the web port 
right into the site's processing loop.
